            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
                <p>The word ΛΗΝΑΙΟΣ is doubtless. It is followed by an alpha and quite a clear circle, which should presumably be read 
                    as omicron = ΑΟ. <!--I cannot see the proposed reading (by whom?) ΠΙΝΩ?  --> The circle that follows alpha in line 1 does not have legs and 
                    therefore cannot be an omega, unless we are dealing with Attic dialect, which is not very likely (see below).
                    The second line of text is hard to work out. There might be two diamond-shaped thetas Θ Θ with space between them - 
                    the angular omicron of  ΛΗΝΑΙΟΣ suggests that possiblity. At the same time, there are many double strokes and slips of the writing tool, so 
                    that some strokes should be counted as accidental. The surface, while convex, was not so difficult for writing, and the writer 
                    had to be either inexperienced or with his hand unsteadied (by drink?). Lenaios is a personal name that comes from the month Lenaion. 
                    It was an Ionian, not Attic month, and was specifically a Milesian and Olbian month, so we should perhaps lean towards expecting the 
                    writer to be Ionian and using Ionian alphabet. Tolstoy no. 75. Rusyaeva 1979, 80-81 discusses the name and the month.</p>
            </div>
